The nest and egg of the black american swift were first discovered by Albert George Vrooman, who was collecting eggs of the Bering cormorant (Phalacrocorax pelagicus) a few kilometers from Santa Cruz in California in 1901[27][30]. Vrooman was one of the many collectors who supported Baird's call for the collection of bird eggs and their further study. At the beginning of the 20th century, Vroomen found and described a large number of California bird eggs
                         
 A Black Swift chick on a nest in British Columbia, 1964
coast, including peregrine falcon (Falco peregrinus), Rallus crepitans, pine siskin (Spinus pinus). However, scientists of the time believed that Vroomen had mistakenly identified the nest and clutch of one of the petrel-like birds.